Business Problem ¶

UNESCO runs an International World Heritage program which catalog and preserve the sites of outstanding importance to common heritage of humankind. So far 1000+ sites are listed under this program and more being added on regular basis. For the people who love to travel and are history, architecture enthusiast this listing may serve as a point of reference.

These sites are situated in variety of terrains and have different levels of accessibility and availability of amenities. For a recreational tourist accessibility and comfort may be preferred while tourists with adventurous tendency may like to use this opportunity explore more.

Problem is, when an individual is planning a vacation will have to research a lot to determine where and what he wants to visit during vacation. Although information is available but scattered. There is no comprehensive way to classify these sites in terms of comfortable or adventurous.Lack of this information leas to unpleasant experience which turns a fun vacation into a unmemorable event. However when individual is aware what he is getting into it makes him prepared to deal with it, which results into a great vacation

My project will create clusters of world heritage sites which in a way will work like recommendation for the tourists to select a group which they would like to visit on their next vacation. Stakeholders are interested in running a guided tours for tourists of recreational inclination to remote sites, their selling point will be arranging comfort and amenities for this cohort to encourage them to enjoy the sites which they would not have seen otherwise.

Data ¶

My primary data source for this project is going to be public websites -

  • UNESCO (https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/)
  • World Heritage Site by Wikipedia (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_Heritage_Site)

I will gather following basic data points -

  • Name of the site
  • Latitude (Required for using Foursquare API)
  • Longitude (Required for using Foursquare API)
  • Country
  • Built-in

I am planning to create a model using heritage sites in Mexico, Greece and India, further I will be only doing this project for the sites of cultural importance. According to current list there are total 72 such sites, therefore I am planning to collect basic data in a excel file manually which I will use in my analysis.

Further to enhance basic data which is needed to achieve the goal of this project I will be using Foursquare API to gather information about all the establishments around each sites I am working with. I will be capturing following information from Foursquare API -

  • Venue Name
  • Venue Latitude
  • Venue Longitude
  • Venue Category

Primary objective is to create clusters of World Heritage Sites with common features defining access from comfortable to underdeveloped, if nearby establishments include hotels, restaurants, railway, airport and other amenities then it will be considered easy approach and good for recreational tourism. However, if no establishments were found then the site will be considered remote and may not be easy to explore and not advisable for recreational tourist. On the other hand, if nearby establishments include historic sites and museums etc. then it will be another good selection for recreational tourist as they will be able to cover more in their visit.

Methodology ¶

Main focus of this project is categorizing the World Heritage Sites into clusters identifying them based on its comfortable access. I will be preparing a model which can be applied to any set of data provided to the model as input to obtain the cluster in which it will fit.

I am planning to use K-Means unsupervised machine learning algorithm for this project. Input data will be list of sites with locational information as discussed in the data section.For training data I will handpick sites in Mexico, Greece and India.

Next step would be gather information about the amenities around these sites so that algorithm can decide if it will comfortable for tourists or challenging depending on the availability of basic amenities. I am planning to use Foursquare API to gather amenities around the sites. I will focus on amenities' availability within the radius of 20 Kilometers of each identified sites.

Upon closely looking at the data acquired from Foursquare I found that data has been categorized very granularly and it also has influence of region and culture. For example when restaurants are categorized Greek Restaurant vs. India vs. Mexican restaurant plus many more other variations then model will become biased and clustering cannot be done based on the fact that food is available near a particular site. This observation is also true with many other types such as accommodation, drinks, museums etc. Therefore I am generalizing categories, specially the ones which are needed for the purpose of this analysis in next step.

In order to established a developed (comfortable) site for recreational tourist it is important that at the minimum site has Food, accommodation and transport nearby. Therefore I will be grouping venues under broader categories, such as Food, Accommodation etc.

While for the tourists who wants a comfortable trip thats a preference but at the same if they can get better value for their money and time it won't hurt. Therefore I will also be further categorizing other features such as more historic sites and waterfront etc.

In this model, sites identified missing basic amenities will be categorized as underdeveloped. This the main goal of this exercise so that stakeholder can plan business around that and tourists can pick their goal for their trip.

  • Food
  • Transport
  • Historic Sites

Accommodation - 9 sites in India and Mexico don't offer any place to stay in vicinity

Food - 9 sites in India and Mexico don't offer any place to eat in vicinity

Transportation - This was an interesting observation. Quite a few sites which offer transportation in its vicinity while Food and accommodation were not available based on the data I acquired. It seems that sites having transportation is in remote area while all other sites have their transportation facility which falls beyond my radius consideration. For example Acropolis, Athens does show any transportation facility which is very unlikely. On the other hand Taj Mahal, India is situated in a comparatively smaller city therefore mode of transports are found within my radius consideration.

May be I should consider collecting transportation data separately, noting if accessible or not¶

Historic Sites - Out of 72 only 16 sites don't offer any other historic sites in the vicinity

Beach - Out of 72 only 18 sites are close to ocean, mostly in Greece and a few in India

Overall - When consider all 5 features together which I am considering to define comfortable tourism vs. adventurous it was found that out of 72, 2 sites have none while other 11 also seem difficult for comfortable tourism

Results and Discussion ¶

Results of analysis using K-Means clustering algorithm using k-factor as 6 has split the data set into following 6 categories -

  1. Urban Setup (Comfortable for Tourists)
  2. City Setup (Easily Doable)
  3. Urban Setup with more to do for tourists (Economical)
  4. Isolated Site (Adventurous)
  5. Remote but Connected
  6. Remote Site and not much to do

This analysis shows that algorithm is working fine and can be used as a reference by tourists and tour operators to plan. I feel some data about the popularity of the sites based on foot-fall or more social-media data about these sites will enhance the quality of the results.

Conclusion ¶

Purpose of the project was to develop a model which will categorize a world heritage site in one of the six clusters discussed in "Result and Discussion" section of this report. Categorization model will help tourists to plan their upcoming trip in a more personalized way by knowing ahead of time, what they are signing up. At the same time stakeholders can also use this report to plan their offering.

Using basic categorization users of this report can further fine tune their trip based on the additional research done about the country and the area they are planning to visit.

From system's perspective I will be working further to enhance dataset using more popularity and social media data to fine tune this model. It was evident while analyzing the data some of the remote sites may not be having enough data as not many people may have reported it to Foursquare.
